data.content:
Yes! Two better options depending on your needs:

**1. `[DataRow]` — simplest for inline constants:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**2. Strongly-typed `DynamicData` (MSTest 3.x+) — when you need computed data:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Why these are better:**

- **`[DataRow]`**: No separate property needed, less boilerplate, test cases are right at the method.
- **Typed `DynamicData`**: Eliminates `object[]` casting, gives compile-time type safety, and produces better error messages when types mismatch.

Use `[DataRow]` for simple constants. Use typed `DynamicData` when test data is computed, loaded from a file, or too complex for attributes.
